{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778549707,"nonce":"5igBdS3ET+RIe7Q3DwuFi9caS10=","message":"**Correction to comment #2 (`f14970a`) — ratio-primary framing was wrong for this matrix.**\n\nThe earlier comment headlined the result as \"no cell beats \u003c 0.5 vel-RMSE-ratio threshold\" and read this as a \"negative result for the lit-replication hypothesis\". This framing is wrong because the within/across pairwise RMSE ratio is the wrong primary metric for this matrix.\n\n**Why the ratio is wrong here.** A within/across ratio is justified only when the conditions being compared are expected to produce systematically different trajectories AND we want to ask whether replicates of one condition cluster tighter than the distance between conditions. In this matrix, every cell is a candidate for the same job — a training-method variant — with no a priori reason for any two cells to produce systematically different velocity profiles. The denominator (nearest-across-cell RMSE) ends up reflecting cost-induced kinematic divergence between cells, not nuisance variation we want to normalise out. The \u003c 0.5 threshold that was pre-registered carries over from a different framing (`baseline_jerk_vrnn_matrix`, where the anchor-vs-conditions reading WAS the right one) and does not apply here.\n\n**Corrected reading — operative metric is absolute within-cell vel RMSE (m/s).**\n\n| Cell | Vel within-RMSE (m/s) | Hold drift (mm) | Peak vel (m/s) |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|\n| lit__flat_jerk | 0.1086 | 22.9 | 0.59 |\n| lit__flat_nojerk | 0.0918 | 24.3 | 0.61 |\n| lit__post_jerk | 0.0423 | 3.3 | 0.79 |\n| lit__full_jerk | 0.0426 | 3.4 | 0.79 |\n| **lit__post_nojerk** | **0.0361** | **2.34** | **0.969** |\n| **lit__full_nojerk** | 0.0414 | 2.74 | 0.964 |\n\n**Substantive POSITIVE finding.** `lit__post_nojerk` (powerlaw `(t/T)^6` post-go, jerk off) wins on every axis: tightest within-cell clustering (~3× tighter than flat), lowest anticipation (~10× lower than flat), fast plausible peak velocity. `lit__full_nojerk` is a close second. Flat schedule (literature-faithful uniform-time target-switching) is what fails, not lit-replication writ large; powerlaw schedule + no jerk is effective.\n\n**Conditional follow-up TRIGGERED.** Residual 2–3 mm hold drift in the winners is above the \u003c 0.5 mm \"good hold\" target. Filed as **`3702f54`** (pre-go-motor-mask follow-up matrix on top of `post_nojerk` / `full_nojerk`).\n\nDoc + figure-spec corrections: `results/f47abb1/notes/variance_analysis.md` rewritten to lead with within-cell RMSE absolute values; `results/f47abb1/figures/rmse_ratio_comparison/spec.json` `metric_description` updated to mark the ratio AUXILIARY. Auth request `388d6576` on branch `feature/f47abb1-ratio-correction`. Cross-cutting metric-pitfall lesson on `4d38c15`; corrective comment on `c99ad9d` (re: comment #18 / `c8909aa`).","files":null}]}